<date>1601328417747</date>< Text>
Looking for a good brunch spot, I came across this place with the beautiful rainbow lattes and had to try it. My fiance and I got the stuffed french toast, breakfast burrito, and rainbow latte during our visit. Overall everything was pretty good! I enjoyed the orange marmalade that was added to the french toast and the fresh strawberries on top. The breakfast burrito was juicy and they had a fabulous salsa to go with it. The rainbow latte was gorgeous but tasted like a normal latte - it's more to visually enjoy and get your Instagram picture. The food was good, but the price ($50 for two people, including tip) was a bit high.

You order your food at the counter inside and then you have the option of taking it to go or eating on the patio. The patio was a bit on the crowded side, even on a Monday morning, and you choose your own seat rather than being told where to sit. I felt there wasn't quite enough distance among the tables and would have preferred if the employees chose seats for the customers. They provided hand sanitizer at the register and at each table which was great!</Text>

< text>
I am in love with this unexpected little restaurant occupying an old gas station in the Glendale hills. The menu puts a foodie spin on classic and simple favorites like grilled cheese, etc. I got the pear and Gorgonzola salad and it was delicious (and huge). My friend got the Brussel sprouts and they were super tasty too! This is super great experience and I highly recommend Wild Oak Cafe.< /text>

<name>Elizabeth Ramos<//name>< date>
1598833608121< /date>
<rate>2< /rate>< Text>
I wanted to try to like this place as it came up on a search.  When I called, one of the young ladies stated that it would be a 30-40min wait if I headed out there. so I thought I'd give it a try anyway.

As we stood in line and proceeded to order, we were told it would be a 30min wait for food if we chose take-out or 30min more or less if we chose to stay and wait for a table.

We waited over an hour. 80 minutes to be precise before we even got our food.

Did I fail to mention that none of the employees check on the outside tables as people come and go?  I would think that they would at least try to check and ask the patrons if they needed assistance or to clean the tables.

The tables themselves aren't quite following the 6ft apart rule.

At this point, we waited so long that their service wasn't as adequate as I thought they'd be.

They need to and should start a wait list for people to be seated... especially on weekends.  I get it... it's a small business, but they need to keep it together.

I know I'll be taking my business elsewhere.  This does not seem like it is well run.  I've been to other establishments that are more truthful and honest about their wait times.  Oh, and those businesses have wait lists through yelp.

One good thing they have going for them is the hand sanitizer at each table.< /Text>

< UserId.>
114434742565737359736<//UserId.>
<username>Martha Ripp<//username><Time>1558260096453<//Time>< rating>
5<//rating>
< text>
At long last and after a pretty long ride (or at least longer than i thought it would be) up Chevy Chase, i made it to the Wild Oak Cafe.
It was a cool sunny morning.  my Starbucks was packed and i had just done some shopping for Christmas dinner (and no it is not too early to begin prep) and then i thought about the Wild Oak.
In any event, I opened the door to this establishment and was greeted by the nice, welcoming face of Miss Ashley who took my order, made my coffee and helped me to figure out the 1/2 and 1/2 dispenser. We also chatted about family, the drive up, the impending Holidays. In other words, her service was super personal and as sunny as the day outside. Corny? Yes but a nice change from frowny, unpleasant service people which seems to be the norm rather than the exception.
The head cook (did not get his name) brought my food over to me and asked if he could bring something else plus he asked me if everything was good as i walked out the door. Good attitude.
The physical plant is well kept, very clean: and this includes the large outdoor patio as well as the smaller area inside.
Decoration is minimal: limited to paint and good furniture both of which seem new and/or well maintained.
There are about 6 parking places right next to the Cafe and there looks to be plenty of street parking.
I ordered:
a Breakfast Bowl
a Cuppa Joe (Peets)
The secret behind producing a good bowl is harder than you might think. All layers must be flavor forward and sit in the bowl in a place where they cannot be overpowered by what is below or on top.
This Breakfast Bowl had fried (as in from the fryer i think) well seasoned potato chunks as a base and they were cooked perfectly and stayed crisp the whole time i was eating.
There were also Scrambled eggs, Bacon, bell pepper, onions, mushrooms, fire roasted Salsa plopped on top as well in 1/4 of a sliced fresh Avocado.
The least successful piece of the bowl were the eggs which were left too long in the pan and therefore a bit stiff and dry. Not bad but not great.
The Salsa (made in house) was tasty and not spicy which was a minor disappointed. Also next time i would order it on the side as it is wet and could soak into the other ingredients.
The fresh, sliced Avocado was a nice foil to the salsa and the other ingredients. This bowl was very good not great.
The coffee was excellent: well brewed and tasty.
I barely touched the depth of their menu but based on this item and the super good service i look forward to returning to the Wild Oak.< /text>

< text>
This cute, what looks like an old gas station converted into a cafe, is perfect little place to get some good food. It has become my wife's and myself new favorite place for breakfast. They are also open for lunch.

My suggestion for breakfast is the breakfast bowls. Really good and tasty. Really reasonable size for the price.

The seating is outside where the gas pumps would of been. The cafe sits next to a golf course. During a nice day it really enjoyable to sit outside and enjoy your food.</text>

Knowledge beyond measure of any style bike for any purpose, a drive to get your bike back on the road better than before and a great source for local riding information.< /Text>

<name>Ilan<//name><Date>1573430022296</Date>< Rating>
5</Rating>
< Text>
I LOVE this place, and the sushi* is fantastic!

*To be fair, every time I come to this place, I go for the omakase menu, sitting at the bar, so it's mostly the nigiri portions.

Let me explain the method, introduced to me by one of my friends.
You sit at the bar so you can see the sushi prepared. You can hear the story behind it. You can talk to the chef Jacky (who is an amazing and hilarious guy) and learn a bit about the amount of work that goes into these small portions of fish. Share some sake, and you will forget that you are in a restaurant and imagine heaven made of sushi (the best type of heaven, of course).
I've been here several times, and this formula (omakase at the bar) never fails. Just let the chef take care of you, you are in good hands.< /Text>

< user_name>

<Time>1578638491676< /Time>< Rating>
5</Rating>
< text>
This was our first visit for dinner, and we had such a great time! Firstly, we were delighted by the "Sushi Tapas" part of the menu, which is not a concept I've heard of before but is great. We tried the Albacore Tataki and the Salmon 5 Ways from that part and enjoyed both very much for the exceptional flavors and quality of fish.

We also ordered the Secret Roll because it was the Chef's Special, and we figured it's probably featuring seasonal fish or flavor combinations we wouldn't have thought to order ourselves. I'm not sure what secrets were in that roll, but it was quite delicious!

We were sitting at the sushi counter, so after our starters, we just ordered a specific number of nigiri and had the chefs pick out the best ones. It was all so delicious. Plus, we learned all kinds of stuff about the differences in growing regions, why you prepare sushi different ways, and best of all, new kinds of fish that we really like and will order in the future.

We had a fabulous experience and look forward to returning! I highly recommend checking this out, especially if you're in the mood for good sushi.< /text>

<userid>113417163814244094081< /userid><name>William ‚ÄúBill‚Äù Owen<//name>< date>
1568531229185< /date>
<Rating>4<//Rating>< Review>
My friends and I sorely miss Minas Brazilian Restaurant and Canto do Brasil, both of which occupied this location for many years. The Japanese restaurant that replaced those Brazilian places, Nakama, is conveniently located by the San Francisco Conservatory of Music, where we had concert tickets, so we decided to give it a try.

Before dining at Nakama, we decided to read all the reviews appearing in three of the major social media and restaurant sites where San Francisco diners tend to post their impressions. We were pleasantly surprised to see that substantial numbers of reviews had already been written for this restaurant that has been open for less than 6 months.

The gist of the reviews seemed to center around two general opinions: (1) the first part of the menu, containing appetizers and tapas had some superb choices; (2) the second part, containing the nigiri and sashimi offerings, did not receive as many accolades, possibly related to the fact that much of the raw fish is shipped to Nakama from far away Japan.

Unlike some of the critical reviews we read, mostly from the early months of this restaurant, we found the service at Nakama to be excellent. We informed our server that we had an 8 PM concert to attend and she made sure that the chef kept our multiple courses arriving in a timely fashion.

Our only service complaint is that we requested miso soup to start but, just as we read in two other reviews, the miso soup never arrived. That said, we were charged for it!

Based on the accolades of prior reviewers, here is what we ordered to build our own personalized tasting menu: grilled live scallop, vegetable gyoza, sake steam clams, Gindara miso black cod, ¬Ω dozen oysters, and eggplant on a skewer. Every one of these plates was superb. Thank you fellow Nakama reviewers!

We also ordered 1 Hamachi nigiri and 1 Hamachi sashimi. It should be noted that you only get ONE nigiri or sashimi per order, not two like you often receive at other sushi restaurants. My dining companion said his Hamachi nigiri tasted OK to him. My Hamachi sashimi had a bit of a stippled, mealy feeling on my tongue, as if it had been frozen, thawed, and frozen again. So, once again, I found the gestalt of previous reviewers of Nakama to be right on.

Nakama offers only two desserts currently: green tea ice cream and green tea cheesecake. We ordered one of each. They were OK but nothing special.

We would consider returning to Nakama but, as other patrons of this restaurant have suggested, we would stick to the first part of the menu and avoid the nigiri and sashimi second half of the restaurant‚Äôs offerings. For less expensive and good quality nigiri and sashimi in an unpretentious atmosphere, Zaoh, a sushi place that has been around forever, is only a block away at Mission & South Van Ness.<//Review>

<rate>3</rate>< review>
Lived there for ~9 months, early terminated to move back to south bay.

Good:
- Good price in this area
- 90% Quiet & good structure to block outside noise
- Staff is good.
- Good gym with squat machine - better than south bay ones.

Bad:
-2 inner-noise. The exhausting pipe is connected to neighbor's living room. They had a crying baby at 6am. And suddenly it became my problem and disrupted my sleep. They should either offer discount or allow people to know what family composition is in their neighbor. Imaging flying a overnight plane every night with a crying baby onboard.
- $300 parking fee - well, it is SF. can't blame anyone
- Still pricy, but it is SF< /review>

< text>
A Lovely Place to Live, With Super Service and Personnel

Rincon Green Apartments is a great place to call home. The community is extremely beautiful, well-kept and peaceful. In fact, everything is so beautiful that I felt like I lived at a resort. The staff always greet residents with a smile, are very attentive to their needs and are quick to attend to any problems that arise. I would like to give special kudos to maintenance worker Andrew and property managers Laila and Janae. Once, I spilled laundry detergent on my apartment's carpet, and I was in a panic because I really don't like the sticky, messy feeling of the laundry detergent residue. I submitted the service request in the morning and Andrew helped me do a deep cleaning of the entire apartment's carpet the same day! What an awesome service! Laila and Janae from the leasing office are super helpful and accommodating. They always try their best to make residents' stay in the community as comfortable as possible. My initial apartment was faced the street, and I couldn't get used to the noise. After learning about the issue, Laila and Janae immediately transferred me to a quiet courtyard apartment at a discounted price. My sleeping quality has since improved significantly!

The apartment could not be in a better location and is close to many shops, grocery stores, restaurants, cafes, bars and transportation options. It offers some of the most cutting-edge designs and boutique amenities in the area. Amenities include a community park, rooftop lounge with a hot tub and grill (I have thrown two BBQ parties here, and my guests had a great time and were extremely satisfied), a 24-hour fitness center, concierge and cyber caf√©, on-site Zipcar and panoramic city views. The apartment is within walking distance of the downtown financial district, SOMA, Google, Facebook, Salesforce, Visa, MasterCard, and all the major tech companies. It is also just a10-minute walk to Embarcadero Boulevard, where you can enjoy breathtaking views of the bay and the Bay Bridge!

In summary, I really enjoyed my time here, as the apartment was very clean, comfortable and had everything I could need! In addition, the maintenance worker is super-efficient, and the office staff are friendly. I will always recommend this fabulous apartment to others!</text>

<Time>1548344398143<//Time><rating>5<//rating><Review>The staff of an apartment building makes all the difference, Rincon Green has very helpful and friendly folks taking care of everything. Also, they are excellent at handling deliveries and packages.

2 years later... Still great!

Rent increases have been reasonable. Two years in a row they offered NO increase IF you renewed early, though sadly not doing that at the moment (Jan 2019)

Did I mention every unit has built in, stacked clothes washer and dryer that they maintain!?  No more shared laundry room nonsense, this was a HUGE point for me personally; your priorities may vary.  And these are small-ish, somewhat compact machines, so you can‚Äôt do ‚Äúgianormous loads‚Äù, but a reasonable amount is fine. Dishwasher is also a bit more narrow than full sized ones, at least in my studio apartment, but it works, just smaller loads.

The next 3 topics may sound like negatives, but it‚Äôs an attempt to keep a well running building, so I‚Äôm not making judgement calls here, just offering ‚Äúfull disclosure‚Äù

Temp parking pass is needed even for an hour, and it‚Äôs $40, even if you only use 1 hour. I‚Äôm guessing they keep it high so SF visitors don‚Äôt use it for a generic parking garage, so it‚Äôs a bit above regular parking garages, but maybe by only $10 or something - parking in SF SoMa/Financial district is expensive, especially if there‚Äôs a game or some other big event.

EV charging: There are a few EV charging station in basement level 2, I forget the service.  3 slots, but there‚Äôs usually a vacant slot. I think you still need to pay the $40 if you‚Äôre a guest, plus the RV service charge.

AirBNB-able?  ABSOLUTELY NOT. SF may allow it in some buildings, but not here. And it can be a first-offense eviction, and the staff knows the tenants pretty well, and there‚Äôs security RFID on the elevators, and I think they maybe even do spot checks for ads, so don‚Äôt do it, you‚Äôll likely be caught and possibly evicted.

Also, zero smoking or vaping, can also be an eviction. And no, going out on the balcony or trying to blow smoke into a vent won‚Äôt work - it‚Äôs a very ‚Äúgreen‚Äù building so smoke doesn‚Äôt dissipate and they will hunt people down if they get complaints.

But again, this is just info to consider, for many of us residents it works out great!<//Review>< Pics>

<review>We love living here so much that we have recently renewed our lease. Although it is not cheap to live here, we appreciate all the valuable services that this building provides, at a very reasonable rate. You could surely get cheaper, but you will have to deal with shady landlords.

Rincon Green is run by Emerald Fund, who have the most fantastic staff: Laila and Vanessa manage the building, while Sarah and Emyli are the friendliest leasing agents around. Make sure you tell them about my review. They organize monthly get-togethers to introduce you to your neighbours. Joey and Cameron watch over the concierge desk during the day, making sure to sign for our deliveries and greeting guests. At nights, there is very friendly security and the park gates are locked. Jerry and Jairell are maintenance and they make sure everything is in tip-top shape. It's a new building, built in 2012, but when we had trouble with the heat and plumbing, they showed up right away!

The building is really lovely, there's Emerald Park as our front yard, with a playground for the little ones to climb on. Inside the building, there's a courtyard with a rock garden and water fountain. If you get a unit with a balcony, it's easy to forget you are actually living in a big city. There is free Philz coffee in the morning, with complimentary tea throughout the day. We really enjoy using the rooftop hot tub after working out in the nice gym on the first floor. And there's also a couple of communal gas grills for quick no-mess dinners.

As for the units, they are a little small, but with good furniture a couple can live comfortably in a 1-bedroom apartment. You can find the floor plans on their website. Each unit comes with apartment-sized appliances: washer, dryer, stove and oven, microwave, and fridge. Since this is an eco-friendly building, there solar-powered heat but no air-conditioning. Since SF doesn't get that hot or cold, we keep the windows open most of the time. If you need a parking space, that's extra, but they do have ports for cars to charge.

We don't really need one, because there are three Zipcars available in the parking garage. And we ride our bikes, which are safely locked up in the storage rooms. You also get Webpass for Internet, which is speedy and reliable. They have Laundry Lockers downstairs if you want someone else to handle your clothes. You can also rent a storage locker, but I think they have a deal with Omni for on-demand storage. And they have a deal with Zeel for discounted massages.

There are a couple of disadvantages though: the sidewalks in the area are often unusable due to the condos popping up all over Rincon Hill. There is also the new Transbay Terminal that is being built, so it does get noisy on the weekends. And since it's close to the Bay Bridge, with its on- and off-ramps, traffic does back up on Harrison St.</review><Pictures>None<//Pictures>< Resp>
None< /Resp>

< Review>
The renovated apartments are nice (not all are renovated, though) and Alameda is just lovely, but the property management company for this apartment complex is the worst I've dealt with in 10+ years of renting.

They weren't even friendly when we signed a lease over two years ago, but that's fine. One particular guy used to go out of his way to harass kids at the pool for doing nothing. But things got much worse with COVID, as they barricaded themselves in their office and refused to answer the phones or emails. The package locker room situation turned into complete mayhem and packages were going missing, but they insisted this was because "residents weren't picking up their package" rather than acknowledging they didn't have nearly enough lockers for a place so big (the same thing would happen during the holidays). I am very sympathetic to the fact that they needed to close the office and all amenities to keep everyone safe and of course agree with that decision, but they never so much as acknowledged that we had 1.5 years of not being able to access the pool and gym, and they made themselves completely unavailable the entire duration of the pandemic.

The worst was when we tried to move out. It took weeks to get them to acknowledge our move-out notice, with repeated calls and emails left unanswered. We had to resort to sliding the letter under the leasing office door several times before we were acknowledged. Now we've moved across the country and we have yet to hear about our security deposit, which is a lot of money, and of course they aren't answering our repeated calls or emails.<//Review>

I have been living here for the past 2,5 years.
Unfortunately my experience is that they don't care about the residents living here, although when you come here first as a potential resident to rent an apartment, they will be very welcoming just to get you sign with them.
The only positive people working here are the maintenance team that is trying hard to solve any maintenance problems. But the people working at the leasing office are unresponsive, inattentive and will not respond to emails or phone calls for days or even at all!
I waited days to get response from Tim about my case, and then when I didn't get any response to my emails or phone calls, I had reach out to Andrea, but again she was neither helpful, neither considerate, and did not show care to resolve my issue.
What a disappointment it has been to receive no help from the leasing office when I needed one. And this has happened to me not only once but a couple of times already.

This is what is lacking from this community.
And maybe this is why you are seeing so many people moving out of here because you don't respect your current residents.<//Review>

We were ready to sign a lease with Summer House but something just didn't feel right; the lack of clarity on the refund of a $200 holding deposit, the lack of email responses from management, and trouble communicating with them, the horrible reviews about these same issues on YELP and Google, and all the added fees ($100/month for a second parking space for example). We also searched the crime report through Trulia, and found there were a high number of reported auto thefts in January 2018. Not what I wanted to see when I'd be paying $100 extra a month for a parking spot that would be in an overflow lot.

We felt like the woman who was handling our application was not on the ball, very inexperienced and not able to give us straight answers. We asked for a full refund on our deposit, including background check since we requested this within 24hrs of putting down the deposit. After much back and fourth by the management, we were finally able to get our money back. When I went to the office to pick up our check, they had a sign on the leasing office that they were closed for a mtg, with the times of closure inaccurate. There were several tenants waiting outside, who told me that "this is how they always are." I am just glad we got our money back and will not be living there.

Please also be aware, the company only accepts Cashiers checks when applying and putting down any initial deposit. My banker found this strange, as a money order and cashiers check is the same from your bank. Only a cashiers check cost $10 to issue as opposed to $5 for a money order. I was told by the same woman doing our application that this is because a money order isn't traceable and a cashier's check is. Wells Fargo seems to think it's because they don't know what they're doing.</Text>

< Review>
Despite all the reviews, I decided to take a look at Summer House after unsuccessful attempts in finding affordable rentals in surrounding neighborhoods. I had lived in Alameda before AND took a look at Summer House 3 years prior. Now, I'm a resident here. I have to say that the new management has changed this place for the better. Now that construction is complete, the grounds are gorgeous with water fountains all around, a gigantic swimming pool and beautiful plants and flowers.  The groundskeepers should be given full credit, as I see them outside everyday working on keeping the place clean and attractive (*reviews have been given about the trash and furniture around the dumpsters, which is accurate still, however, this is at the fault of the residents, not the property managers). The ordinary apartments are comparable to their going rates, so if you are looking for something plain to get you through the year, this is a great spot. They come with a double sink, dishwasher, electric stove, microwave, carpeted rooms, and easy cable hookup. So far we've had to call maintenance twice in the 3 months that we've been here. Though some appliances were not working properly when we moved in, the maintenance people were there on time and fixed our problems right away... no questions asked. Be careful for the "water fee" which is divided among the complex as a whole and attached to your monthly rent. There is ample parking but the car gates are not secure. Plenty of kids here who play in the complex when school is out. We live with a 10 year-old so he made friends right away. Last note, it can get a little noisy since the walls are pretty thin. I would suggest sticking with a top floor.</Review>

< Text>
Summer house apartments are a great option if you're moving into the bay. When I moved into Alameda 2 years ago I found their prices to be competitive and even though they raised my rent it's still below market value. They're dog friendly, pretty responsive, and the units themselves are on the nicer side. Everyone in my building is pretty chill and I haven't heard about any noise problems.
Cons:
- Not everyone is good with their own dog and I've seen several incidents where on-leash dogs were being really aggressive with other dogs (not the apartment's fault but it's still something to be aware of).
- We've had a few minor annoyances with maintenance but we don't call them very often.
- Sometimes non-residents will get into the habit of letting themselves into the complex. Nothing dangerous though. Example: For a few weeks a guy would use a stick every day to let himself into one of the parking lot areas and just make calls all day in front of my building. I guess it wouldn't have been an issue if he wasn't glaring at all of the residents that walked by.<//Text>

< review>
It was a bad omen when I went to the bank for a cashier's check for rent and deposit, and the teller told me I should tear it up find a new place if I hadn't signed anything yet.  These have been my negative experiences in the one year I have lived here:

1. My roommate and I voiced concern over parking on the tour.  Our guide said, "The 3 bedroom apartments come with 2 spaces."  This is an outright lie. The excuse: "Oh, sorry, he is new here."

2. We were told the prices of the apartments are all reflected on the website.  We applied for our apartment based on website listing, and then the contract was for $200 more per month.  Their excuse was, "Sometimes there's a significant delay between the website updates and actual rent changes, especially during the summer when there are a lot of moves."

3. After signing a lease for $200 more than expected and one fewer parking space, a new blank lease appeared in our email  a month later asking for even more money.  They said there was an error, and we weren't being charged enough.  They didn't push it after we pointed out this was blatantly illegal, but they still act like they're doing us a huge favor and we're just trying to scheme them out of cash.

4. There is a significant amount of noise at night.  I was particularly peeved one night when a car with a custom engine and very loud after stock muffler was parked below my window at 1:30 AM just revving the engine over and over again.  Then the guy left the doors open on both sides and BLASTED his stereo.  I was going to call security, but when I looked again, I saw that it was the security guard.  I had to be at work 5 hours later.

5. Management is in cahoots with some local towing company, and they call them immediately if anything is amiss.  If you need to unload groceries because you don't have enough parking spots that come with the apartment, you're gambling if it will be there when you return, even if it's only 10 min.

6. People like to dig through the dumpster below my bedroom window on a daily basis, and they can be rather loud at times, too.

7. There are loud children everywhere.  Make sure your apartment isn't next to the parking lot or the playground.

8. You are next to 2 schools, which is convenient if you have kids, but a pain around 8AM and 3PM.

9. There's a creepy old guy in the complex across the street who just walks up and down the sidewalk and calls police for people who are parked illegally, even if you tell him you just need to run a bag of groceries upstairs before you hunt for parking elsewhere.

Basically, I should have listened to my bank teller.  I'm moving in a week, and I can't wait.<//review>

< text>
I really liked living here. Here are the pros and cons:
Pros:
- Management office: People in the management office are very nice and helpful. I did not deal with all of them (they look very nice though), but I usually talk to Britnie, she is very very nice girl and very helpful. Always optimistic :)
- Price: Apartment price was very nice especially if u work in SF, though they require very good credit, and relatively high income to be able to live there
- Maintenance: They respond very quickly, usually less than 24 hours
- Facilities: Swimming pool, Gym, playground for kids, barbecue area
- Security: Place has gates and security guards at night.
- unit: has microwave and dishwasher
- Commute: bus station is 5 mins walk. 25 minutes Bus to SF, 5 mins to Oakland.

Cons:
- Washers are very good, but dryers were not that great. However, I knew that they will have pretty new washers/dryers on January 2016
- Sometimes, you hear people's footsteps above you, but its okay for me.
- Carpet in my apartment was not that new.< /text>

< review>
I pass by Citydog! Club all the time just to see the cute happy pups playing inside, and just recently had the pleasure of taking my dog Lucky to have his first grooming appointment here! The online booking system was seamless and easy to use, and I actually greatly appreciate that the team took the time to check our pet vaccination record even if we were just coming in for a groom and not daycare/boarding. Lucky is a shy but sweet rescue boy who is usually scared around other dogs, and Westley took care of him with the utmost gentleness and kindness. I got both a courtesy text and call to notify me when Lucky was ready. I believe when the grooming is done but you haven't arrived yet, they offer the option of letting your pup hang out in the play area to make friends, but since Lucky is still working on his socialization skills, I marked on the online appointment form that I would like to respectfully decline this offer. When I arrived to pick Lucky up, he was brought to the front from a private separate area. This is another A+ for Citydog! Club because they (1) are kind enough to offer to let your pup have a short playdate while you're on your way to pick them up and (2) respected and paid attention to my request to let him rest on his own for today. As for the haircut, my Lucky looked so very handsome and happy! I truly feel that Westley and the team went above and beyond, and I would recommend Citydog! Club to anyone seeking top quality pet grooming with top shelf customer service. Lucky and I look forward to coming back real soon! :)</review>

< text>
This Review is ONLY about DAYCARE SERVICES

My current puppy is my first ever pet so you can imagine (like a first kid), I overthink everything and only want the best for him/spoil him. My puppy has gone to various day cares since he was 10 weeks old an d now he's 13 months. I look for variety in facilities he is approved to go to (outdoor, indoor, pool time, types of dogs, you name it) CityDog! is by far the cleanest facility he has ever gone to and he has a great time. The staff and evaluators do a good job keeping the dogs with like attitudes and also allow the dogs to switch between play areas as appropriate. I also love that the play areas face the public street so that people walking by can peek in. Even throughout COVID, they have been ensuring they take all cautionary measures to limit any and all contact between humans. The staff wear gloves and masks when handling the dogs. They have also been allowing everyone to pre-purchase daycare packs at the new member rate to assist people in these uncertain times. For those who work long hours, they are open 7:00 am - 9:00 pm and work with your puppy/dog on taking naps to keep them at top shape and you can schedule mealtime during their day for a nominal fee.

Overall, this place couldn't have been a better find for us. I have also heard from a close neighbor that they have great grooming services as well at a competitive and reasonable price point.< /text>

<Text>I left my pup here for 2 weeks and was very nervous because it's the longest I've ever left him (he is a high-energy pit mix and has separation anxiety). The Citydog team took such good care of him, sent lots of pics, and were super responsive to all of my questions and outreach. I've had a couple of very bad Rover experiences so finding this gem was truly a life saver and will 10/10 be returning!

I should add: I called over a dozen boarding facilities before I found Citydog! and was highly concerned to discover that the vast majority crate dogs ~6pm to ~8am and circulate them in and out of their crates throughout the day  for ~2-4 hours of daily playtime. I couldn't have left my dog in a situation like that in good faith, and was AMAZED that City dog lets the dogs play / roam free ALL day (something like 8a-9p) and if you don't pay additional for a nightly private suite (which I didn't) they get to stay in the run with the other dogs through the night. <rate>5< /rate>< review>
***Disclaimer, I never take time to write a review, but this review is necessary***

If you're looking for a doggy daycare/boarding facility, look no further. I'll start this by stating that prior to relocating to the Bay Area, I used to take my dog to Citydog's! other facility in San Diego. After relocating to the bay in January, I struggled to find a daycare/boarding facility to take my fur baby to. I was running into concerns where I felt my dog was either not 100% safe and/or well cared for. Other facilities also lacked cleanliness as well as looked more like a penitentiary.

On Wednesday 7/24, I received an email notification that Citydog! had opened a location in Mountain View. I immediately knew my struggle of searching for the perfect facility was now over. I showed up to Citydog! yesterday and both my dog and I were graciously greeted by the staff and provided a tour from the Regional Manager, Diana. This facility is beyond perfect and will exceed all of your expectations. The dog handlers were very friendly and upbeat. You can easily see that they take their jobs seriously and will provide the utmost care/love for your dog. After my tour, I can say that this facility is essentially the Ritz Carlton for dogs. Now I can take a much needed vacation knowing that my dog is in the best hands possible (a side from my own).

Thank you Citydog! Club- your core value of MTFL (make them feel loved) will be a staple in the Bay Area!

***UPDATE: recently read a review from a disgruntled customer and I can confidently say that no dogs are left unattended in the play park. There is a divider in between the large and small dog park. The handlers are taller than the gate and can easily view both sides from either park. The divider has a section that opens, so the handler has immediate access to either side. I would NEVER leave my dog at a facility that lacks safety. You can watch your dog on the webcam to prove it. Also, after being a highly satisfied customer of Citydog‚Äôs sister location in San Diego for over 2 years, it‚Äôs disappointing to read a meritless review. I love this new location and the amazing staff. We will be forever customers as long as we live here.</review>

< Text>
It is a typical big pet store with just about every brand of pet food available in the USA.  I have cats so i don't visit the dog side of the store.  The cat area is well laid out, easy to find whatever you are looking for.   If you cannot find something the staff will help you AFTER you find them.  I usually have to walk to the front of the store and ask a check-out clerk to use the P.A. system to call for help.  The staff is excellent once you find them.  Be persistent.</Text>
